---
import BaseLayout from '../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
---

<BaseLayout
  title="Survival Guide"
  description="Part II: The Survival Guide — practical strategies for alienated parents in the acute phase. Legal options, communication, and protecting your mental health."
>
  <section class="section section-dark hub-hero">
    <div class="container-narrow" style="text-align:center;">
      <p class="part-label">Part II</p>
      <h1>The Survival Guide</h1>
      <p class="hub-intro">
        Practical strategies for the acute phase: legal options, communication tactics,
        and how to protect your mental health when everything is falling apart.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Overview -->
  <section class="section">
    <div class="container-narrow prose">
      <p class="lead-text">
        When you are in the middle of parental alienation — the legal battles, the silence
        from your child, the sense of powerlessness — what you need most is not theory.
        You need things you can actually do.
      </p>
      <p>
        This section is built on the Alienated Parent Resilience and Survival Model —
        a layered framework that organises the chaos into manageable dimensions. It draws
        on clinical research, legal strategy, and the hard-won experience of parents who
        have walked this path before you.
      </p>
      <p>
        The approach is honest. Not everything here will fix your situation. Some of it
        is about damage limitation. Some is about positioning yourself for the long term.
        All of it is about keeping you standing, functional, and connected to the parent
        your child will one day need you to be.
      </p>

      <div class="model-image-wrap">
        <a href="/images/alienated-parent-survival-and-engagement-model-love-over-exile.png" target="_blank" rel="noopener" title="Click to view full size">
          <img
            src="/images/alienated-parent-survival-and-engagement-model-love-over-exile.png"
            alt="The Alienated Parent: Survival and Engagement Model — a layered framework covering health and safety, support team, communication strategy, staying connected, avoiding traps, and the long haul"
            width="800"
            height="800"
            loading="eager"
            decoding="async"
            class="model-image"
          />
        </a>
        <p class="model-caption">Click the image to view full size</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Survival layers -->
  <section class="section section-alt">
    <div class="container">
      <p class="section-eyebrow">The framework</p>
      <h2 class="section-heading">Layers of survival</h2>
      <p class="section-subhead">
        The Alienated Parent Resilience Model breaks survival into layers. You cannot
        work on communication tactics if your mental health is collapsing. You cannot
        build a legal strategy if your basic safety is not secured. Start at the bottom.
      </p>
      <div class="layers-grid">
        <div class="layer-card card">
          <div class="layer-number">1</div>
          <h3>Health and Safety</h3>
          <p>
            Maslow's hierarchy applies: you cannot solve a love and belonging crisis when
            your physical and mental health are in freefall. Sleep, nutrition, exercise,
            and professional mental health support come first — not as luxuries, but as
            the foundation everything else is built on.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div class="layer-card card">
          <div class="layer-number">2</div>
          <h3>Your Support Team</h3>
          <p>
            A therapist who understands alienation (not one who "sees both sides" of abuse).
            A lawyer with a general's mindset, not a counsellor's. A support group of people
            who know exactly what this feels like. And an inner circle you can trust completely.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div class="layer-card card">
          <div class="layer-number">3</div>
          <h3>Communication Strategy</h3>
          <p>
            The BIFF method for co-parent communication: Brief, Informative, Friendly, Firm.
            The Yellow Rock approach. Strategic documentation of every interaction. Every
            message you send should pass the "would a judge read this favourably?" test.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div class="layer-card card">
          <div class="layer-number">4</div>
          <h3>Staying Connected</h3>
          <p>
            Contact matters more than comfort. The Breadcrumb Strategy — consistent, caring
            signals during silence. Breaking the trance with ordinary moments. Proactive
            clarification without demanding agreement. Keeping the door open without
            being walked over.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div class="layer-card card">
          <div class="layer-number">5</div>
          <h3>Avoiding the Traps</h3>
          <p>
            The Logic Trap — debating a delusion backfires every time. The temptation to
            overcompensate. Permissive parenting born from fear. The holding pattern where
            life goes on pause. Recognising these traps before you fall into them.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div class="layer-card card">
          <div class="layer-number">6</div>
          <h3>The Long Haul</h3>
          <p>
            The Stockdale Paradox: hold unwavering faith that you will prevail AND brutal
            realism about where you are now. This is a marathon. Hope must not harden into
            expectation. Patience is a survival skill, not a personality trait.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Key tools -->
  <section class="section">
    <div class="container-narrow prose">
      <h2>Practical tools that work</h2>
      <p>
        The survival guide is not about positive thinking or motivational slogans. It is
        a set of specific, tested tools and techniques drawn from conflict resolution,
        family law, trauma therapy, and the lived experience of alienated parents.
      </p>

      <h3>The BIFF Method</h3>
      <p>
        Developed by Bill Eddy at the High Conflict Institute. Every written communication
        with your co-parent should be: <strong>Brief</strong> (no essays),
        <strong>Informative</strong> (facts, not feelings), <strong>Friendly</strong>
        (neutral-to-warm tone), and <strong>Firm</strong> (clear position, no negotiation
        on boundaries). This protects you legally and emotionally.
      </p>

      <h3>The Sphere of Influence</h3>
      <p>
        Three circles: what you can <strong>control</strong> (your behaviour, your health,
        your responses), what you can <strong>influence</strong> (professional opinions,
        the long-term narrative), and what you can only <strong>observe</strong> (the other
        parent's behaviour, court timelines, your child's immediate choices). Redirect
        every drop of energy from the outer circle to the inner one.
      </p>

      <h3>The Cognitive Diet</h3>
      <p>
        Deliberate control of what information you consume. When you're being gaslit by
        an entire system, your intake matters. Educational content, supportive communities,
        professional guidance — in. Doom-scrolling, unsolicited advice, and toxic forums — out.
      </p>

      <h3>Strategic Journaling</h3>
      <p>
        Two types, both essential. The <strong>emotional dump</strong> — raw, uncensored,
        for your eyes only (Dr James Pennebaker's expressive writing research). And the
        <strong>factual log</strong> — dates, times, what was said, by whom — evidence
        you may need in court.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Article preview -->
  <section class="section section-alt">
    <div class="container">
      <p class="section-eyebrow">Articles</p>
      <h2 class="section-heading">Start reading</h2>
      <div class="articles-preview">
        <article class="article-preview-card card">
          <span class="article-tag">Survival Guide</span>
          <h3><a href="/articles/how-to-cope-with-parental-alienation">How to Cope With Parental Alienation: A Framework for the Acute Phase</a></h3>
          <p>
            When you're in the middle of it, the world feels like it's collapsing. Here is
            a structure that has helped parents survive the worst periods.
          </p>
          <span class="article-meta">12 min read</span>
        </article>
      </div>
      <p style="margin-top:2rem;">
        More articles are being published regularly.
        <a href="/articles">See all articles →</a>
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- CTA -->
  <section class="section section-dark" style="text-align:center;">
    <div class="container-narrow">
      <h2>Get the free Survival Guide</h2>
      <p style="opacity:0.8; margin-bottom:2rem; max-width:540px; margin-inline:auto;">
        A distilled, practical resource covering the most essential frameworks
        and strategies — designed for parents in the acute phase.
      </p>
      <div style="display:flex; gap:1rem; justify-content:center; flex-wrap:wrap;">
        <a href="/free-guide" class="btn btn-primary">Download the Guide</a>
        <a href="/inner-freedom" class="btn btn-outline-light">Part III: Inner Freedom →</a>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

</BaseLayout>

<style>
.hub-hero { padding-block: 6rem; }
.part-label {
  font-size: 0.78rem;
  font-weight: 600;
  letter-spacing: 0.12em;
  text-transform: uppercase;
  color: var(--color-amber-light);
  margin-bottom: 1rem;
}
.hub-intro {
  font-size: 1.1rem;
  color: rgba(247,243,238,0.8);
  margin-top: 1.25rem;
  line-height: 1.75;
}
.lead-text {
  font-size: 1.15rem;
  line-height: 1.75;
  color: var(--color-charcoal);
  margin-bottom: 1.5rem;
}
.section-eyebrow {
  font-size: 0.78rem;
  font-weight: 600;
  letter-spacing: 0.1em;
  text-transform: uppercase;
  color: var(--color-amber);
  margin-bottom: 0.5rem;
}
.section-heading { margin-bottom: 1rem; }
.section-subhead {
  font-size: 1rem;
  line-height: 1.7;
  color: var(--color-charcoal);
  max-width: 680px;
  margin-bottom: 2.5rem;
}

.layers-grid {
  display: grid;
  grid-template-columns: repeat(3, 1fr);
  gap: 1.5rem;
}
.layer-card {
  padding: 2rem;
  position: relative;
}
.layer-number {
  font-family: var(--font-serif);
  font-size: 2.5rem;
  font-weight: 700;
  color: var(--color-green-deep);
  opacity: 0.15;
  line-height: 1;
  margin-bottom: 0.5rem;
}
.layer-card h3 {
  font-size: 1.1rem;
  margin-bottom: 0.75rem;
  color: var(--color-green-deep);
}
.layer-card p {
  font-size: 0.92rem;
  line-height: 1.7;
  color: var(--color-charcoal);
}

.articles-preview { max-width: 680px; }
.article-preview-card { padding: 2rem; }
.article-preview-card h3 {
  font-size: 1.1rem;
  margin-bottom: 0.5rem;
}
.article-preview-card h3 a {
  color: var(--color-green-deep);
  text-decoration: none;
}
.article-preview-card h3 a:hover { color: var(--color-amber); }
.article-preview-card p {
  font-size: 0.92rem;
  line-height: 1.7;
  color: var(--color-charcoal);
}
.article-tag {
  font-size: 0.72rem;
  font-weight: 600;
  letter-spacing: 0.06em;
  text-transform: uppercase;
  color: var(--color-amber);
  background: rgba(196,154,60,0.1);
  border-radius: 4px;
  padding: 0.2em 0.6em;
  display: inline-block;
  margin-bottom: 0.75rem;
}
.article-meta {
  font-size: 0.82rem;
  color: var(--color-warm-grey);
  margin-top: 0.5rem;
}

.model-image-wrap {
  margin-top: 2.5rem;
  text-align: center;
}
.model-image-wrap a {
  display: inline-block;
  border-radius: 12px;
  overflow: hidden;
  transition: box-shadow 0.2s;
}
.model-image-wrap a:hover {
  box-shadow: 0 4px 20px rgba(0,0,0,0.12);
}
.model-image {
  width: 100%;
  max-width: 680px;
  height: auto;
  border-radius: 12px;
  border: 1px solid var(--color-border);
}
.model-caption {
  font-size: 0.82rem;
  color: var(--color-warm-grey);
  margin-top: 0.75rem;
  font-style: italic;
}

@media (max-width: 900px) {
  .layers-grid { grid-template-columns: repeat(2, 1fr); }
}
@media (max-width: 600px) {
  .layers-grid { grid-template-columns: 1fr; }
}
</style>
